  "prompt": "Are shares debt or equity?",
  "response": "Shares represent equity in a company. When you purchase shares, you are buying a small ownership stake in the company. This entitles you to a portion of the company's profits, which may be paid out in the form of dividends, and gives you voting rights in certain corporate matters. Debt, on the other hand, refers to money borrowed by the company that must be repaid over time, typically with interest. Examples of debt instruments include bonds and loans. Therefore, shares are considered equity, not debt.",
